# Raycasting

Raycasting shoots an invisible ray from the camera through a screen point into the 3D scene and returns any objects it hits.

```
const raycaster = new THREE.Raycaster();
const mouse = new THREE.Vector2();

// Set normalized device coordinates (-1..1)
mouse.x =  (e.clientX / innerWidth)  * 2 - 1;
mouse.y = -(e.clientY / innerHeight) * 2 + 1;

// Configure ray from camera through mouse point
raycaster.setFromCamera(mouse, camera);

// Test against an array of meshes
const hits = raycaster.intersectObjects(meshArray);
if (hits.length > 0) {
  const first = hits[0].object; // closest hit
  const point = hits[0].point;  // 3D world position
}
```

# Mouse Coordinate Normalization

The raycaster expects Normalized Device Coordinates (NDC) in the range −1 to +1. Screen pixels must be converted:

```
// For full-window mouse:
mouse.x =  (e.clientX / window.innerWidth)  * 2 - 1;
mouse.y = -(e.clientY / window.innerHeight) * 2 + 1;
```

When the canvas doesn't fill the whole window (common in the IDE preview pane), use the canvas bounding rect:

```
const rect = ctx.renderer.domElement.getBoundingClientRect();
mouse.x =  ((e.clientX - rect.left) / rect.width)  * 2 - 1;
mouse.y = -((e.clientY - rect.top)  / rect.height) * 2 + 1;
```

This is the correct approach in Artlab — always use the canvas rect.

# Keyboard Events

Listen on window for keyboard events and store the handler so it can be removed in teardown():

```
let _onKey;

export function setup(ctx) {
  _onKey = (e) => {
    if (e.key === 'r') resetAll();
    if (e.key === 'g') toggleGrid(ctx);
  };
  window.addEventListener('keydown', _onKey);
}

export function teardown(ctx) {
  window.removeEventListener('keydown', _onKey);
}
```

Use `e.key` for printable characters and named keys (`'ArrowLeft'`, `'Escape'`, `'Enter'`, `' '` for space). Use `e.code` for physical key positions (layout-independent).

Prefix keys with modifiers: `e.shiftKey`, `e.ctrlKey`, `e.altKey`.

# Clean Teardown

Artlab calls teardown() when switching to a new example. Failing to clean up causes event listener leaks that accumulate across every example load.

The teardown() checklist:

```
export function teardown(ctx) {
  // Remove DOM event listeners
  window.removeEventListener('mousemove', _onMouseMove);
  window.removeEventListener('click',     _onClick);
  window.removeEventListener('keydown',   _onKey);

  // Remove DOM elements this example created
  _hudElement?.remove();

  // Stop audio / video streams
  _cam?.stop();

  // Dispose Three.js resources (optional but good practice)
  mesh.geometry.dispose();
  mesh.material.dispose();
}
```

Three.js objects added with ctx.add() are automatically removed from the scene by PreviewPane when teardown is called. You only need to manually dispose geometries and materials if you created many unique ones.
